column4: <content>Stay in Italy. For longer stay in Italy speeks the fact that Clovio was in Rome only 1553-1556 so Bruegel workinbg with him may well have stayed in Rome into 1554. From Rome he may have made the trip to Naples. Itinary can be partly reconstructed by works. Journey through France proved by 'Leon in France'. Stay in Italy: 2 prints 1553, Tivoli, Fondi drawing, Ripa Grande (?), Naples Harbour, Battle of Messina (Reggio), Palermo, Triumph of Death. Return: Tyrol, Martinswand, Walterspurg.</content>
<part_of.title>Bruegel. Biography: Details about Italian Journey, Birth, Death dates, Place of birth, Clovio, Ortelius, Theatrum Orbis, Bruegel's ship drawings used.</part_of.title>
<parts.title>Bruegels frühe Werke: Stadtansichten (Lyon, Neapel), Biblische Themen: Babel, wohl auch als Landschaft, Miniaturen.</parts.title>

<parts.title>[2 vouwbladen [vouwblad 1]] B.M. [plaatskenmerk] Reggio. G. Braun & F. Hogenberg, [Civitates orbis terrarum] Theatri praecipuarum totius mundi urbium liber sextus. Anno 1618 Dedication signed by Antonius Heirat & Abraham Hogenberg, pl. 58 [...]; [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. Nothing of Bruegel's charcter preserved - whereas Huys has really done so. Like in Huys Reggio on left Messina  [...] Reggio; [vouwblad 2] Reggio II. Many views of Austria and Bohemian towns bear the remark: Depinxit et communicavit Georgius Houfnaglius Delineatur a folio R° 1617 [...][scan]</parts.title>

<parts.title>Bruegel's Journey to Italy: 1) Lyon; 2) Fondi; 3) Reggio 1552 Messina; 4) Palermo. Pal Sclafani; 5-6) Etchnings Bast. 1 & 2, Rome 1553; 7) Ripa Grande; 8) Tivoli; 9) Tessin Tal; 10) Gotthard; 11, 12, 13) Graubünden-Vorderrhein; 14) Martinswand.</parts.title>
